Fancy Histograms!

Weâll start by making some histograms.

#install.packages("dslabs")
library(dslabs) 
## Warning: package 'dslabs' was built under R version 4.4.3
data(heights)
glimpse(heights)
## Rows: 1,050
## Columns: 2
## $ sex    <fct> Male, Male, Male, Male, Male, Female, Female, Female, Female, Mâ¦
## $ height <dbl> 75, 70, 68, 74, 61, 65, 66, 62, 66, 67, 72, 72, 69, 68, 69, 66,â¦

This data is the heights of humans, divided by their biological sex.

Use ggplot to make a histogram of all of the heights:

library(ggplot2)

ggplot(heights, aes(x = height)) +
  geom_histogram(binwidth = 1, fill = "blue", color = "white") +
  labs(
    title = "Distribution of Heights",
    x = "Height (inches)",
    y = "Frequency"
  ) +
  theme_minimal() +
  theme(plot.title = element_text(hjust = .5))

Change up the binwidth and see how the plots change. Try 1, 5, 10, and 20

ggplot(heights, aes(x = height)) +
  geom_histogram(binwidth = 20, fill = "blue", color = "white") +
  labs(
    title = "Distribution of Heights",
    x = "Height (inches)",
    y = "Frequency"
  ) +
  theme_minimal() +
  theme(plot.title = element_text(hjust = .5))

Smooth this out to an emperical density with geom_density()

ggplot(heights, aes(x = height)) +
  geom_density(fill = "blue", alpha = 0.5) +
  labs(
    title = "Distribution of Heights",
    x = "Height (inches)",
    y = "Frequency"
  ) +
  theme_minimal() +
  theme(plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5))

Use a new argument in the aes(), group = to split this density by sex

ggplot(heights, aes(x = height, group = sex, fill = sex)) +
  geom_density(alpha = 0.5) +
  labs(
    title = "Distribution of Heights by Sex",
    x = "Height (inches)",
    y = "Frequency"
  ) +
  theme_minimal() +
  theme(plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5))

OR we can do it with color or fill. If you say you want to color by sex, R knows that you want a different curve for each of them.

ggplot(heights, aes(x = height, color = sex, fill = sex)) +
  geom_density(alpha = .25) +
  labs(
    title = "Distribution of Heights by Sex",
    x = "Height (inches)",
    y = "Frequency"
  ) +
  theme_minimal() +
  theme(plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5))

If youâve used fill, then there is now a slight issue that they are overlapped. We can fix this with alpha transparency!

ggplot(heights, aes(x = height, color = sex, fill = sex)) +
  geom_density(alpha = 0.3) +
  labs(
    title = "Distribution of Heights by Sex",
    x = "Height (inches)",
    y = "Density"
  ) +
  theme_minimal() +
  theme(plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5))

Letâs make some boxplots of the same information.

ggplot(heights, aes(x = sex, y = height, fill = sex)) +
  geom_boxplot() +
  labs(
    title = "Heights Distribution by Sex",
    x = "Sex",
    y = "Height (inches)"
  ) +
  theme_minimal() +
  theme(plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5))

Quantatitive summaries:

Find the mean and median overall.

mean(heights$height)
## [1] 68.32301
median(heights$height)
## [1] 68.5

Find the mean and median for both groups.

heights %>% 
  group_by(sex) %>% 
  summarize(
    mean_height = mean(height),
    median_height = median(height)
  )
## # A tibble: 2 Ã 3
##   sex    mean_height median_height
##   <fct>        <dbl>         <dbl>
## 1 Female        64.9          65.0
## 2 Male          69.3          69

How tall is the tallest woman? How short is the shortest man?

heights %>%
  group_by(sex) %>%
  summarize(
    tallest = max(height),
    shortest = min(height)
  )
## # A tibble: 2 Ã 3

# data for presidental elections
votedata <-  presidentialElections

## Rows: 1,097
## Columns: 4
## $ state   <chr> "Alabama", "Arizona", "Arkansas", "California", "Colorado", "Câ¦
## $ demVote <dbl> 84.76, 67.03, 86.27, 58.41, 54.81, 47.40, 48.11, 74.49, 91.60,â¦
## $ year    <int> 1932, 1932, 1932, 1932, 1932, 1932, 1932, 1932, 1932, 1932, 19â¦
## $ south   <lgl> TRUE, FALSE, TRUE, FALSE, FALSE, FALSE, FALSE, TRUE, TRUE, FALâ¦

Letâs look at the democratic vote by state for 2000. We canât use geom_bar for a bar chart, since we have the category in one variable and the âheightâ of the bar in another. We need geom_col()

Make a bar graph of the democratic vote by state in 2000.

ggplot(data = votedata, aes(x = state, y = demVote)) +
  geom_col() +
  labs(
    title = "Democratic Vote by State (2000)",
    x = "State",
    y = "Votes"
  )

Well this looks awful. We have two options: swap the x and y or the more fun soundingâ¦ Coordinate flip!

Use coord_flip() on the previous graph to make it better.

ggplot(votedata, aes(x = reorder(state, demVote), y = demVote)) +
  geom_col() +
  coord_flip() +
  labs(
    title = "Democratic Vote by State (2000)",
    x = "State",
    y = "Votes"
  )

I donât love the squashed together coordinates, but itâs a display window issue.

So. This is a helpful graph, but it would be more helpful if it was ordered. Use x = reorder(x_variable, y_variable) in aes() to order the x variable by the y variable

ggplot(votedata, aes(x = reorder(state, demVote), y = demVote)) +
  geom_col() +
  coord_flip() +
  labs(
    title = "Democratic Vote by State (2000)",
    x = "State",
    y = "Votes"
  )

So, what if I want to see what the north and south states did different?

start with a facet_wrap using the south variable:

ggplot(votedata, aes(x = reorder(state, -demVote), y = demVote)) +
  geom_col() +
  coord_flip() +
  facet_wrap(~south) +
  labs(
    title = "Democratic Vote by State (2000)",
    x = "State",
    y = "Votes"
  )

Okay, thatâs not great. Lets color by south instead.

ggplot(votedata, aes(x = reorder(state, -demVote), y = demVote, fill = factor(south, labels = c("Non-Southern", "Southern")))) +
  geom_col() +
  coord_flip() +
  labs(
    title = "Democratic Vote by State (2000)",
    x = "State",
    y = "Votes",
    fill = "Region"
  )

Iâm a good data scientist, so I want my plot to have a name! and my axes to have lables! Use labs to add a title, subtitle, and x and y labels.

ggplot(votedata, aes(x = reorder(state, -demVote), y = demVote, fill = factor(south, labels = c("Non-Southern", "Southern")))) +
  geom_col() +
  coord_flip() +
  labs(
    title = "Democratic Voting Patterns Across US States",
    subtitle = "State-level Democratic Vote Counts in the 2000 Election",
    x = "State (Ordered by Democratic Votes)",
    y = "Number of Democratic Votes",
    fill = "Region"
  )

You can move the legend with theme(legend.position = "bottom")

ggplot(votedata, aes(x = reorder(state, -demVote), y = demVote, fill = factor(south, labels = c("Non-Southern", "Southern")))) +
  geom_col() +
  coord_flip() +
  labs(
    title = "Democratic Voting Patterns Across US States",
    subtitle = "State-level Democratic Vote Counts in the 2000 Election",
    x = "State (Ordered by Democratic Votes)",
    y = "Number of Democratic Votes",
    fill = "Region"
  ) +
  theme(legend.position = "bottom")

What else could we facet by? years! Letâs filter to year in 2008 and 2016, then facet by years.

votedata %>%
  filter(year %in% c(2008, 2016)) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = reorder(state, -demVote), y = demVote, fill = factor(south, labels = c("Non-Southern", "Southern")))) +
  geom_col() +
  coord_flip() +
  facet_wrap(~year) +
  labs(
    title = "Democratic Voting Patterns Across US States",
    subtitle = "State-level Democratic Vote Counts in 2008 and 2016",
    x = "State (Ordered by Democratic Votes)",
    y = "Number of Democratic Votes",
    fill = "Region"
  ) +
  theme(legend.position = "bottom")

We need to know who won! We could add a vertical line at 50 for who got more, to indicate the majority of votes. Adding the layer geom_hline() adds a horizontal line. (What do you guess geom_vline() would do?)

votedata %>%
  filter(year %in% c(2008, 2016)) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = reorder(state, -demVote), y = demVote, fill = factor(south, labels = c("Non-Southern", "Southern")))) +
  geom_col() +
  geom_hline(yintercept = 50, linetype = "dashed", color = "black") +
  coord_flip() +
  facet_wrap(~year) +
  labs(
    title = "Democratic Voting Patterns Across US States",
    subtitle = "State-level Democratic Vote Counts in 2008 and 2016",
    x = "State (Ordered by Democratic Votes)",
    y = "Number of Democratic Votes",
    fill = "Region"
  ) +
  theme(legend.position = "bottom")

Getting fancy with a map!

When using geom_polygon or geom_map, you will typically need two data frames:

  • one contains the coordinates of each polygon (positions)
  • the other the values associated with each polygon (values).

An id variable links the two together.

Run the below code to get a map graph.

library(maps)
## Warning: package 'maps' was built under R version 4.4.3
## 
## Attaching package: 'maps'
## The following object is masked from 'package:purrr':
## 
##     map
votedata$state <- tolower(votedata$state)  ## states need to be lowercase for linking

states_map <- map_data("state") ## this gives us the lat and long for each point of each state.
  
map_plot <-  ggplot(data =  votedata %>% filter(year == 2008), aes(map_id = state)) +
    geom_map(aes(fill = demVote), map = states_map) +
    expand_limits(x = states_map$long, y = states_map$lat)
map_plot  

map_plot <-  ggplot(data =  votedata %>% filter(year == 2016), aes(map_id = state)) +
  geom_map(aes(fill = demVote), map = states_map)+
  expand_limits(x = states_map$long, y = states_map$lat)
map_plot

What if I want a map that shows which of the states are âsouthâ? What do I change?

map_plot <- ggplot(data = votedata %>% filter(year == 2008), aes(map_id = state)) +
  geom_map(aes(fill = factor(south, labels = c("Non-Southern", "Southern"))), map = states_map) +
  expand_limits(x = states_map$long, y = states_map$lat) +
  labs(
    title = "Southern States in 2008",
    fill = "Region"
  )
map_plot

Some more dplyr practice

I want to know the average democratic vote for N vs S, by year.

First, find the average democratic votes for the north and the south, every year. Youâll need to do a double group_by() here. You do it in one call of the function.

votedata %>%
  group_by(year, south) %>%
  summarize(avg_dem_vote = mean(demVote, na.rm = TRUE))
## `summarise()` has grouped output by 'year'. You can override using the
## `.groups` argument.
## # A tibble: 44 Ã 3
## # Groups:   year [22]
##     year south avg_dem_vote
##    <int> <lgl>        <dbl>
##  1  1932 FALSE         56.7
##  2  1932 TRUE          83.4
##  3  1936 FALSE         59.2
##  4  1936 TRUE          83.2
##  5  1940 FALSE         52.8
##  6  1940 TRUE          80.9
##  7  1944 FALSE         51.1
##  8  1944 TRUE          75.1
##  9  1948 FALSE         50.2
## 10  1948 TRUE          45.9
## # â¹ 34 more rows

Then, letâs plot that! Pipe the result of your group_by and summarize to ggplot and geom_line(), with year on the x axis and your summarized value on the y axis. Color by the south variable.

votedata %>%
  group_by(year, south) %>%
  summarize(avg_dem_vote = mean(demVote, na.rm = TRUE)) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = year, y = avg_dem_vote, color = factor(south, labels = c("Non-Southern", "Southern")))) +
  geom_line() +
  labs(
    title = "Average Democratic Vote by Region Over Time",
    x = "Year",
    y = "Average Democratic Vote",
    color = "Region"
  )
## `summarise()` has grouped output by 'year'. You can override using the
## `.groups` argument.

We can use boxplots to visualize the distribution of weight (body_mass_g) within each species:

ggplot(penguins, aes(x = species, y = body_mass_g, fill = species)) +
  geom_boxplot() +
  labs(
    title = "Penguin Body Mass by Species",
    x = "Penguin Species",
    y = "Body Mass (g)"
  )
## Warning: Removed 2 rows containing non-finite outside the scale range
## (`stat_boxplot()`).

What if we also want the points? Layering!! Add a geom_point to your existing boxplot. geom_boxplot + geom_point!

ggplot(penguins, aes(x = species, y = body_mass_g, fill = species)) +
  geom_boxplot() +
  geom_point() +
  labs(
    title = "Penguin Body Mass by Species",
    x = "Penguin Species",
    y = "Body Mass (g)"
  )
## Warning: Removed 2 rows containing non-finite outside the scale range
## (`stat_boxplot()`).
## Warning: Removed 2 rows containing missing values or values outside the scale range
## (`geom_point()`).

But, these are all stacked upâ¦ to actually see them, use âgeom_jitterâ instead of points

ggplot(penguins, aes(x = species, y = body_mass_g, fill = species)) +
  geom_boxplot() +
  geom_jitter() +
  labs(
    title = "Penguin Body Mass by Species",
    x = "Penguin Species",
    y = "Body Mass (g)"
  )
## Warning: Removed 2 rows containing non-finite outside the scale range
## (`stat_boxplot()`).
## Warning: Removed 2 rows containing missing values or values outside the scale range
## (`geom_point()`).

How to get the boxplots on top? The layers are plotted in the order you give them, so change to geom_point + geom_boxplot. (You might want to change the alpha on the boxplot to be able to see the plots under them)

ggplot(penguins, aes(x = species, y = body_mass_g, fill = species)) +
  geom_jitter() +
  geom_boxplot(alpha = 0.25) +
  labs(
    title = "Penguin Body Mass by Species",
    x = "Penguin Species",
    y = "Body Mass (g)"
  )
## Warning: Removed 2 rows containing non-finite outside the scale range
## (`stat_boxplot()`).
## Warning: Removed 2 rows containing missing values or values outside the scale range
## (`geom_point()`).

Maybe letâs try replacing the boxplot with a geom_violin()?

ggplot(penguins, aes(x = species, y = body_mass_g, fill = species)) +
  geom_jitter() +
  geom_violin(alpha = 0.5) +
  labs(
    title = "Penguin Body Mass by Species",
